      <TR>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'>Sssyx</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> Ok, it's late and I'd rather be playing so here's a quick critique.  This is not line-by-line but I'll hit the bigger points.</P><P>Velous, please understand that I am not making any personal judgements or attacks.  You are more motivated than I am, I haven't written in years and that alone puts you ahead of me.  This is just some stuff that I picked up along the way.</P><P><i>Velous said</i><BR><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=2 face="Verdana" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote><BR>... Here is a section from what I have written.</P><P>"It is time," I heard some old grey voice echoing around me like thunder.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana" size=2 id=quote></P><P><BR>Ok, I kinda get what you are going for here but let me comment.  The juxtapostion of senses is a nice trick, describing a voice as "grey" is a nice touch.  It sets a tone and style to your writing but too much of it will quickly get tiresome.  The thunder simile is cliche though.  Everything echos like thunder, even if you don't consider it an expression it is commonly used.  </P><P><BR><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=2 face="Verdana" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote><BR> I was then placed in shackles and their icy fine steel death grip hurt my wrists and ankles like hell. I almost choked as a cold goblet was thrust at my mouth pouring some vile burning acidic liquid down my throat. Whatever it was, it burnt my insides with an unquenchable black fire as it went to my stomach and the rest of my body. I felt myself going numb as the sickness came over me. My arms and legs became as heavy as the marble pillars that supported the Great Library of Neriak. I began to fall towards the abyss as I lost my balance. I could feel the unnatrual strength of my bindings as they held me partialy upright. Then the darkness started to devour me as I heard someone scream.<BR><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana" size=2 id=quote></P><P>You have a mix of some good and bad stuff in here, but a thesaurus and some tightening up could go a long way.  I'll say one thing plainly, you have a true love of adjectives.  Expressions like "icy fine steel death grip",  "vile burning acidic liquid", and "unquenchable black fire" are all very descriptive and convey some intense feeling, but they are cumbersome phrases that should be shortened.  They are also not concret images that the most readers have a common experience with.  Ponder, just what does an icy fine steel death grip feel like, just what is vile burning acidic liquid, and just what the hell is an unquenchable black fire?  The last few lines of this section suffer from this problems as well - an abyss? somebody forgot to tell me there was an abyss! What does an abyss look like anyway? Unnatural strength of my bindings? Damn, if it were just that icy cold steel I'm sure I could break out!</P><P>Okay, okay, I'm just kidding around there but I hope you get my point.  So far your story is more like an evil Monet painting than say a vivid and twisted Picasso.</P><P>More on this later too.  </P><P><BR><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=2 face="Verdana" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote><BR>The black hole of blinding darkness drew closer as I fell into it at a lightning speed that would make any bard envious.<BR><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana" size=2 id=quote></P><P>Along the same lines as what I said about concrete imagery above, this is just kinda muddles.  If you want to say you fell into a hole so fast that a bard would be impressed, try finding something that moves fast enough to impress a bard and then compare yourself to it directly.  Don't make me do it for you.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=2 face="Verdana" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote><BR> Then my universe was shattered by this pain that just seemed to become me. It enveloped me and held onto my soul like an unholy leach draining my sanity dry. I felt comforted by the Darkness, the Pain... then there was nothing. No gods, no paradise, no altered plains of existance, just an empty void with me in it...</P><P>/snip</P><P><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana" size=2 id=quote></P><P><BR>Ok, I'm petering out and I'm not looking forward to the flames I'm guessing I'll be getting for expressing my opinion so I'm going to talk about a basic problem that it very common among amateur writers:</P><P>Concrete Imagery</P><P>Good writing consists of a few basic things: conflict, good grammar and spelling, character development and concise writing that leaves no question in the readers mind about what the writer is talking about (By no means a comprehensive list, just some of the most important basics.) Concrete imagery is one of the most important things a writer can provide.</P><P>When you say thinks like "I felt myself going numb..." you lose a good opportunity to give me an image.  I've personally never felt myself go numb so I have no idea what you mean, I can only guess.</P><P>Earlier I made a poke at the "unnatural strength of my bindings" line, for the same reason.  Have I ever been bound?  Well in my case yes, by handcuffs as well as by plastic tie on different occasions, but, you know what? Most people aren't me.  Even putting aside the fact that the average person probably has very little experience being bound, to further stretch the image by attributing another relatively ambiguous quality to the bindings only further removes the reader from the experience.  Just what is "unnatural strength?"  Are the bindings alive?  Can you feel them pulsing and clammy against your skin?  Do they burn you physically because they are cold, despite the torturously hot conditions of the room?  </P><P>Really, this is your big weakness to focus on.  Vague images are nice for Top 40's radio, but if you are trying to tell me a story then quit yanking my crank and tell it.  Don't tell me about "It enveloped me and held onto my soul like an unholy leach (SP? there btw) draining my sanity dry."  Tell me about the blood pooled around your father's tortured corpse that always haunts you at times like this, or something at least.  I've never been enveloped by darkness, I've never had my soul held onto by an unholy leech, and as far as I know, I've never had my sanity drained dry.</P><P>I'm not trying to be mean, just saying that if you want to rise above the great unwashed hoards and write something that people will want to read that working on the things I've talked about would be a very good start.</P><P><b>I AM the angry leeezurd!</b></P><P><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=22254" target="_blank" target="_blank">Sssyx Syxyx</a></P><P><a href="mailto:sssyx@mmdog.com">sssyx@mmdog.com</a></P><P></font></td>
      </tr>
